V. 78. The infection has spread, and will farther spread, like inurrain among sheep. or scurf in pigs‚ or contagious rot from grape to grape. You will go on to something worse than this. The height of wickedness is reached by slow degrees. Soon we shall see you among those who mock the rites of Bona Dea, driving out the women, and keeping up such orgies as the Baptae tire Cotytto with. They wear long garlands on their heads and jewels on their neck, and sacrifice, and pour libations. Here one paints his eyebrows and makes his eyes look languishing: another drinks from an obscene glass with his long locks tied up in a net of gold, with a handsome tunic, while his slave swears by his master's J uno! Semiramis and Cleopatra did not so. V. 143. But this is less than noble gladiators, who scour the arena, better born than all the fine folk who look on by the podium, yea than the great man too who gives the gamae. The fables about manes, Styx, and Charon’s boat we leave to babes. But only think them true, and what would all those mighty spirits say when such a shade came down! They'd cry for lustral water, sulphur, pine, and laurel.
